@DATABASE "djpeg.guide"
@INDEX "ImageEditor.guide/INDEX"
@FONT helvetica.font 13
@SMARTWRAP

@NODE MAIN "ImageEditor - Loader: JPEG [djpeg]"
@TOC "Loader.guide/MAIN"

@{LINDENT 4}
@{PAR}@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{B}JPEG@{UB}@{FG TEXT}@{LINE}
@{PAR}@{B}Decompress JPEG file to portable anymap.@{UB}@{LINE}
@{PAR}Decompresses the named JPEG file and produces an image file as portable anymap.@{LINE}
@{LINDENT 8}@{LINE}
@{B}Extract Grayscale only@{UB}@{LINE}
@{LINDENT 12}
    Force gray-scale output even if JPEG file is color. The Loader runs noticeably faster in this mode.@{LINE}
@{LINDENT 8}@{LINE}
@{B}Scale to@{UB}@{LINE}
@{LINDENT 12}
    Scale the output image by a factor. Currently the scale factor must be 100%, 50%, 25%, or 12.5%.
Scaling is handy if the image is very large. The Loader runs much faster when scaling down the output.@{LINE}
@{LINDENT 8}@{LINE}
@{B}DCT@{UB}@{LINE}
@{LINDENT 12}
    Use the seleced Discret Cosinus Transformation method.
The float method is very slightly more accurate than the int method,
but is much slower unless your machine has very fast floating-point hardware.
Also note that results of the floating-point method may vary slightly across machines,
while the integer methods should give the same results everywhere.
The fast integer method is much less accurate than the other two.@{LINE}
@{LINDENT 4}
@{PAR}See also the @{" JPEG " LINK "cjpeg.guide/MAIN"} saver.@{LINE}
@{PAR}[@{B}djpeg@{UB}] @{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{I}Copyright (C) 1991 by Independent JPEG Group @{UI}@{FG TEXT}@{LINE}

@ENDNODE
